My response is more with Mr. Hunt than with Mr. J.T.Miller. It is difficult to seperate the emotion from the facts. Especially if the subject is one that you are attached with. Again , I state that my problem was not what I did in Vietnam but with the way I was recieved when I got Back. I quickly learned not to talk or tell anyone that I was a vet. I find that today I watch the History Channel's presentation of the 10,000 Day war with wonder.  Because I didn't know when it was over or what was going on lest I expose myself to my friends as a vet. I too, despise Mrs. Ted Turner and all that she stood for.  I too STILL fail to understand the lack of support. I STILL can't abide the failure to serve our country.  I guess that is a narrow view. But it is a honest and sincere emotion. <br>
Ah, but logic! There is the rub! I still can't put logic and common sense and history in front of my emotional scarring.  Folks, I swear to God, that I will NEVER accept any explanation of logic for what the protestors did to me and my brothers morale when I was in country. I'm sorry that I can't see that point of view . I realize that those who protested against the wars feel or felt as passionately as I do.  But....but...but.   Peace.
